z={name:Vz,description:"Ask the user questions before proceeding with a design. When starting something new, you should use this tool liberally. Use it when you are about to make design choices the user might want to override — layout direction, color palette, content tone, interaction patterns, etc. Call this at the start of a new design task, before writing any files, and when the user's prompt is ambiguous. For each question, provide the question text and a list of possible answers. The FIRST option should always be the preferred, most likely correct direction — this is the answer you will assume if the user does not respond. The user sees a card with dropdowns for each question and can change any of them. If the user changes answers and submits, you'll get a follow-up message with the corrections — adjust your work accordingly. Set isSvg: true on a question to provide SVG visuals instead of text options. Each option must be a small, self-contained SVG string with a viewBox (roughly square). Keep SVG items simple — wireframe layouts, color swatches, icon arrangements, simple shapes. No heavy detail or embedded images. Call this AFTER doing any exploration or research (reading files, reviewing references, etc.) but BEFORE creating a plan or starting work.",input_schema:{type:"object",properties:{questions:{type:"array",items:{type:"object",properties:{question:{type:"string",description:"The question to ask"},options:{type:"array",items:{type:"string"},description:"Possible answers, preferred/most likely first (first = default). When isSvg is true, each option is an SVG string with a viewBox."},isSvg:{type:"boolean",description:"When true, options are SVG strings rendered as visual thumbnails. SVGs should be simple (wireframe layouts, color swatches, icon arrangements), roughly square, and include a viewBox."}},required:["question","options"]},description:"List of questions for the user"}},required:["questions"]}};function Zz(e){return`The user has requested that 